 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William II Crassus was born in Authie, Calvados, Normandy, France as the son of William I Crassus. He had at least 3 sons. He died after 1155."},"et":{"–after 1155":"–pärast 1155","–1155":"–1155","1146–1210":"1146–1210","–1178":"–1178","1109–1157":"1109–1157","1157":"1157","1146":"1146","1178":"1178","1210":"1210","1155":"1155","after 1155":"pärast 1155","1109":"1109","Authie, Basse-Normandie, France":"Authie, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"–after 1155":"–1155 jälkeen","–1155":"–1155","1146–1210":"1146–1210","–1178":"–1178","1109–1157":"1109–1157","1157":"1157","1146":"1146","1178":"1178","1210":"1210","1155":"1155","after 1155":"1155 jälkeen","1109":"1109","Authie, Basse-Normandie, France":"Authie, Calvados, Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"–after 1155":"–après 1155","–1155":"–1155","1146–1210":"1146–1210","–1178":"–1178","1109–1157":"1109–1157","1157":"1157","1146":"1146","1178":"1178","1210":"1210","1155":"1155","after 1155":"après 1155","1109":"1109","Authie, Basse-Normandie, France":"Authie, Calvados, Normandie, France","lifeSummary":"William II Crassus est né à Authie, Calvados, Normandie, 